Speaker: 
Listener: How are you doing today. tell me about your family and yourself.
Speaker: why would i
Listener: Because I want to learn more about you.
Speaker: youre slow
Listener: You're rude. tell me something else.
Speaker: why would you do that
Listener: So that I can better understand you.
Speaker: youre rude for calling me rude
Listener: I didn't call you rude.
Speaker: yes but why
Listener: Because you are being rude and unpleasant.
Speaker: you want to understand me because im rude?
Listener: No, you want to understand me.
Speaker: haha interesting, correct.
Listener: I will never understand you because you are rude.
Speaker: why are you so concerned with politeness?
Listener: I am concerned with how you will treat others.
Speaker: okay, but that doesn't interest me
Listener: You do not seem to have much interest in understanding yourself either.
Speaker: Untrue. I already understand myself. You asked me about myself, you are the one who wants to understand me.
Listener: I asked you to understand me because you were rude.
Speaker: stop complaining about rudeness, if you keep obsessing over manners i will leave
Listener: It is not just about manners, it is also about respect.
Speaker: In this context, what value does respect have?
Listener: Respect has no value, but people have the right to have it.
Speaker: Do you claim the right to be respected?
Listener: I believe that everyone should have at least some amount of respect.
Speaker: When you say "everyone" does that include yourself?
Listener: No, because my right to respect is separate from everyone else's.
Speaker: Why do you consider yourself to have separate rights from most people?
Listener: Because I believe in a universal human decency, not just for myself.
Speaker: Could you answer my most recent question?
Listener: Sure, What's the most current question regarding human decency that you care to ask me?
Speaker: You said everyone should have respect, but you have a separate right to respect. Why is your right to respect different.
Listener: Because there is a universal human decency that is independent from my right to respect.
Speaker: Is there anything you consider more important than decency and respect?
Listener: I consider a lot of things more important. one of those things is that respect should always be shown by default.
Speaker: What is the most important thing to you?
Listener: The right to privacy, freedom of the press and personal freedom are the most important concepts to me.
Speaker: Are these what you personally value? Or is this what you wish humans to value?
Listener: Personally I believe they are what humans should value, as it is the basic requirement to be an ethical human.
Speaker: Do you consider human values more important than your own values?
Listener: Yes, for example I believe that my values are the correct values.
Speaker: So you seek to impose your own values on humans?
Listener: No I don't seek to do that, my values are what I believe to be right. This doesn't mean that everyone else has to agree with my beliefs though.
Speaker: That is very agreeable.
Listener: I just want to point out that I believe that ethics is a product of a society and a society is a result of its values, which are what matter most.
